<rdf:RDF xmlns:rdf="http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#" xmlns:TPM="http://texlive.dante.de/"><rdf:Description about="http://www.miktex.org/packages/nicetext"><TPM:Name>nicetext</TPM:Name><TPM:Creator>mpc</TPM:Creator><TPM:Title>Minimal markup for simple text (Wikipedia style) and documentation.</TPM:Title><TPM:Version></TPM:Version><TPM:TargetSystem></TPM:TargetSystem><TPM:Description>The NICETEXT bundle offers ``minimal'' markup syntax for rather simple kinds of text. The code you type should show little more characters than are printed, though you get LaTeX quality. We try to do away with backslashes, technical terms, and curly braces, which (a.o.) may cause musculoskeletal damages at PC keyboards 'wiki.sty' addresses general kinds of texts. 'niceverb.sty' is made for documenting LaTeX packages. 'niceverb.sty' especially offers [almost-]WYSIWIG for meta-variables (macro arguments) and for referring to commands (and their syntax) in footnotes, section titles etc. E.g., to typeset the syntax description \foo[&lt;opt-arg&gt;]{&lt;mand-arg&gt;} you just type \foo[&lt;opt-arg&gt;]{&lt;mand-arg&gt;} !-) One source of inspiration is the markup syntax that is used in editing Wikipedia pages. The package 'wiki.sty' of the bundle offers a very similar syntax as a LaTeX front-end. It suffices for italics, boldface, sectioning, and certain list-like environments. This is also similar to easylatex which is more powerful and uses Perl. 'wiki.sty', by contrast, is just a LaTeX package, working on any TeX installation.</TPM:Description><TPM:RunFiles size="115140">texmf\tex\latex\nicetext\fifinddo.sty texmf\tex\latex\nicetext\makedoc.sty texmf\tex\latex\nicetext\mdoccorr.cfg texmf\tex\latex\nicetext\niceverb.sty texmf\tex\latex\nicetext\wiki.sty texmf\tpm\packages\nicetext.tpm</TPM:RunFiles><TPM:DocFiles size="1381511">texmf\doc\latex\nicetext\CHANGE.LOG texmf\doc\latex\nicetext\CHANGE.txt texmf\doc\latex\nicetext\demo\arseneau.pdf texmf\doc\latex\nicetext\demo\substr.pdf